      "issue_number": 2,
      "action": "comment",
      "comment_body": "Two concrete bugs in the planned coercion/filter logic worth fixing before implementation:\n\n1. NEUTRAL boolean mapping will silently produce all-NaN. `pd.read_csv` auto-recognizes the literals `TRUE`/`FALSE` (and `True`/`False`) as booleans, so the `NEUTRAL` column will very likely arrive already as `bool` dtype — not `object`. Applying `.map({\"TRUE\": True, \"FALSE\": False})` to an already-bool Series maps every value to NaN (the bool keys don't match the string keys), turning the column to `object` and failing the `df[\"NEUTRAL\"].dtype == bool` acceptance assertion. Fix: branch on dtype — if `is_bool_dtype`, leave it; otherwise normalize case first, e.g. `s.astype(str).str.strip().str.upper().map({\"TRUE\": True, \"FALSE\": False})`. Add a fixture row where pandas pre-parses neutral to bool to lock this in.\n\n2. `wc2026_schedule()` filter is too broad. `tournament == \"FIFA World Cup\"` matches every World Cup in the 49,477-row history (1930–2022), not just 2026 — it will return thousands of historical fixtures. The filter must additionally constrain to the 2026 cycle, e.g. `DATE >= \"2026-01-01\"` (or a year predicate). The acceptance criterion 'returns tournament == \"FIFA World Cup\" rows including unplayed fixtures' should be tightened to '...for the 2026 edition', and the test fixture should include a historical-WC row that must be excluded.\n\nScope is otherwise cohesive (single data source) — no split needed."
    },
    {
      "issue_number": 3,
      "action": "comment",
      "comment_body": "The played/remaining partition has an unhandled status gap. The documented `status` enum is `FINISHED | IN_PLAY | PAUSED | TIMED | SCHEDULED`, but `tournament_state()` is specified only as 'partitions group-stage matches into played vs remaining_group_fixtures (by status)' — which leaves `IN_PLAY` and `PAUSED` unassigned. This matters because an `IN_PLAY`/`PAUSED` match has non-null partial `fullTime` scores but is NOT a final result; bucketing it as 'played' would feed a non-final scoreline into the historical join, and bucketing it as a 'remaining fixture' misrepresents it too. Make the rule explicit: treat only `FINISHED` as `played`; `TIMED`/`SCHEDULED` as `remaining_group_fixtures`; and decide `IN_PLAY`/`PAUSED` deliberately (recommend excluding from both, or a separate `in_progress` field) so no partial score leaks into either bucket. Add an acceptance criterion and an `IN_PLAY` group-stage fixture to the test set covering this case."
    },
    {
      "issue_number": 4,
      "action": "comment",
      "comment_body": "Two correctness points for the pure rules, both touching the 'deterministic' guarantee:\n\n1. `rank_third_places` needs a terminal tiebreak. Ordering the 12 third-placed teams by points → GD → GF can still leave teams fully tied (common with synthetic/early data), and Python's sort is stable but its input order here is not guaranteed canonical, so the qualifying-8 selection can become input-order-dependent. Add a final deterministic key (e.g. group letter alphabetical) so the cut between 8th and 9th best third is reproducible regardless of input ordering.\n\n2. `assign_thirds` must fail loudly on uncovered combinations. There are C(12,8)=495 valid qualifying-third combinations. The acceptance criterion permits the lookup to 'document the canonical subset it covers' — but if the table is partial, `assign_thirds(frozenset)` will raise a bare `KeyError` (or worse, silently mis-slot) for any uncovered combination, and `resolve_r32` would then emit a malformed bracket. Require `assign_thirds` to raise a clear `ValueError` naming the missing combination when it's absent, and add a test exercising that path. Prefer encoding all 495 rows from the official FIFA WC2026 table; if only a subset ships, the criterion should state that uncovered combinations raise rather than being treated as 'ok'."
    }
  ]
}
